## Project Overview

This project involved designing an instrumented **3/8-inch drive torque wrench** rated for  
**600 in·lbf**, integrating analytical calculations, CAD modeling, strain-gauge placement,  
and ANSYS finite-element validation.

The wrench was required to meet:

- Sensitivity ≥ 1.0 mV/V  
- Yield/brittle failure factor of safety X₀ ≥ 4  
- Crack-growth safety factor Xₖ ≥ 2  
- Fatigue safety factor Xₛ ≥ 1.5  
- Compatibility with standard bonded foil gauges  
- Manufacturability with consistent, repeatable strain fields  

---

## Baseline Analysis

Using the assigned baseline dimensions, the following performance metrics were obtained:

- **Deflection:** 0.091 in  
- **Maximum bending stress:** 12.8 ksi  
- **Strain at gauge:** 375 µε  
- **Estimated half-bridge output:** 0.38 mV/V  

### Baseline Safety Factors

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Failure Mode</th><th>Safety Factor</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Static Strength</td><td>28.9</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Crack Growth</td><td>2.95</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Fatigue</td><td>8.98</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

The baseline design is structurally adequate but **does not meet the sensitivity requirement**, motivating a redesign of the geometry.

---

## Improved Final Design

The redesign focused on:

- Introducing a reduced cross-section to amplify measurable strain  
- Maintaining yield, fatigue, and fracture safety factors  
- Providing flat, accessible gauge bonding surfaces  
- Ensuring smooth strain gradients across the gauge region  

